</style>

<ServiceHero
  title="Dryer Vent Repair Across Southern California"
  subtitle="Transition duct, lint-trap housing, booster fan, exterior vent-flap, the appliance-side portion of dryer venting. Honest scope boundary. Same-day across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino & Riverside counties. $89 diagnostic."
  heroImageTitle="Dryer Vent Repair"
/>

<!-- INTRO + SCOPE BOUNDARY -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01, About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">Appliance-side dryer vent repair, and an honest boundary on what we don't do.</h2>

        <p>Dryer venting is a cross-category service. The appliance-repair trade handles the dryer itself, the motor, heat source, drum, belt, thermal fuse, electronics. The dryer-vent-cleaning trade handles the venting pathway from the dryer to the exterior of the home, transition ducts, in-wall and in-ceiling runs, booster fans on long installs, exterior vent terminations, roof caps. There's an overlap in the middle, and this page is about that overlap.</p>

        <p>Our scope on dryer venting is appliance-side: the short run from the dryer cabinet to the wall connection, the lint-trap housing, the vent collar on the back of the dryer, the booster fan if one sits in-line on the appliance-side portion of the vent, and the exterior vent-flap when it can be accessed without a ladder or roof work. That work overlaps directly with dryer service, the parts, the diagnostic approach, and the tools are the same ones we use on dryer calls.</p>

        <p>What we don't do: the vent-pathway cleaning work that the dryer-vent-cleaning specialist trade is set up for. Full home-vent-system cleaning with rotary brushes and high-volume vacuums. Roof-cap terminations that require ladder or rooftop safety gear. Multi-story apartment building shared vent systems. Fire-code compliance certification inspections. Those are specialist jobs done daily by companies with the right equipment and safety certifications for that work specifically. When a diagnostic call turns out to be a cleaning job rather than a repair job, we say so and refer you.</p>
      </div>

      <aside class="sticky-cta">
        <div class="cta-label">Same Day Dryer Vent Repair</div>
        <a href={phoneHref} class="cta-phone">{phone}</a>
        <a href={phoneHref} class="btn-cta">Call Now, We Pick Up</a>
        <a href="/book/" class="btn-cta" style="background:#222; margin-top:-4px;">Book Online</a>
        <div class="cta-sub">Mon–Fri 7am–9pm · Sat Mon–Sat 8am–8pm · Sun closed · Phone answered 24/7</div>
        <hr class="cta-divider" />
        <ul class="cta-detail">
          <li>$89 diagnostic, applied to repair</li>
          <li>Appliance-side scope only</li>
          <li>Transition duct + lint-trap housing</li>
          <li>Booster fan + vent-flap repair</li>
          <li>BHGS #A49573, EPA 608 Universal certified #1346255700410, · Insured</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- SCOPE: WHAT WE DO / DON'T DO -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Honest Scope Boundary</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What's in our scope, and what's a cleaning-specialist job</h2>
    <p class="lead">This category is dominated by dryer-vent-cleaning specialists for a reason: they do the cleaning portion better than any generalist appliance-repair company would. We handle the repair portion that overlaps with dryer service. Clear boundary up front.</p>

    <div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr; gap:22px; margin-top:28px;">
      <div class="scope-box yes">
        <h3>✓ SDAR appliance-side scope</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Transition duct replacement (4-inch short run from dryer to wall)</li>
          <li>Lint-trap housing replacement and cleaning</li>
          <li>Vent-collar repair at back of dryer (where the duct connects to the unit)</li>
          <li>Booster-fan replacement (in-duct supplemental fans on long runs)</li>
          <li>Exterior vent-flap or vent-door replacement (when accessible without roof or ladder)</li>
          <li>Appliance-side restriction diagnostic (is the dryer's performance issue vent-caused?)</li>
          <li>Dryer-side disambiguation (is it actually a vent problem or a heating-element or thermal-fuse issue?)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="scope-box no">
        <h3>✗ Cleaning-specialist scope, not us</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Full home vent-system cleaning (rotary brushes + high-volume vacuums)</li>
          <li>Long vent runs through walls, ceilings, and attic spaces</li>
          <li>Roof-cap vent terminations requiring roof or ladder access</li>
          <li>Multi-story apartment and condo building shared vent-system cleaning</li>
          <li>Fire-code compliance inspection and certification</li>
          <li>Commercial laundromat, multi-unit, and commercial-plant dryer venting</li>
          <li>Vent-path reconstruction or re-routing (general-contractor scope)</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem; color:#a02010; font-weight:600; margin-top:14px; padding-top:12px; border-top:1px solid #e0b0a0;">For those scopes we refer to dedicated SoCal dryer-vent-cleaning companies, Dryer Vent Wizard, LA Dryer Vent, Elim Dryer Vent Cleaning, DryerXpert, A-1 Air Duct in LA County, plus regional specialists serving Orange, Ventura, and the Inland Empire, all with the right equipment and certifications.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- COMMON SYMPTOMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Common Symptoms</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When appliance-side dryer vent repair is the answer</h2>
    <p class="lead">Not every "dryer not working right" call is a vent problem, and not every vent problem is an appliance-side vent problem. Our diagnostic establishes which is which before any repair order is written.</p>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Extended Drying Times</h3>
        <p>The most common vent-related symptom. A partially restricted transition duct or a lint-buildup at the appliance side of the vent reduces airflow; the dryer runs longer cycles to reach dryness. If the restriction is appliance-side (transition duct, lint trap, vent collar), that's our scope. If it's further along the run through walls or ceilings, that's cleaning-specialist territory.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Dryer Running Hot</h3>
        <p>When vent airflow is restricted, heat accumulates in the dryer cabinet instead of venting outside. The back of the dryer feels unusually hot, cycles may end early on a safety trip, and in severe cases the thermal fuse or high-limit thermostat can trigger. We check appliance-side vent restriction and dryer-side heat controls together.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Visible Damage to Transition Duct</h3>
        <p>Crushed, torn, kinked, or disconnected transition duct between the dryer and the wall. This is the single most common appliance-side vent repair, the flexible transition duct gets crushed when the dryer is pushed back against the wall, or torn when the dryer is moved for cleaning behind it. Replacement runs in the $80–180 labor plus parts range.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Visible Lint at Back of Dryer</h3>
        <p>Lint escaping around the connection where the transition duct meets the dryer's vent collar indicates a poor seal, a cracked collar, or a disconnected duct. In the short term this means lint accumulation in the laundry-room space; over time it means reduced venting effectiveness and heat buildup. Appliance-side repair, our scope.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Exterior Heat or Reduced Airflow at Termination</h3>
        <p>The exterior vent-flap or vent-door may have failed in the closed or partially-closed position, restricting airflow out of the home. If it's accessible from ground level or a short step-stool, we can replace it. If the termination is on a roof cap or second-story wall requiring ladder or rooftop work, that's a cleaning specialist or general contractor job.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Booster Fan Failure</h3>
        <p>Homes with long vent runs sometimes have an in-duct booster fan installed to maintain airflow. When the booster fan fails, the vent effectively becomes an extended run with no assist, dry times extend significantly. Appliance-side booster fan replacement is our scope. Fan assembly replacement runs $120–250 labor plus $80–200 parts depending on specific unit.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top:36px; padding:24px; background:#fafafa; border:1px solid #e8e8e8; border-radius:8px;">
