<!-- FIRE SAFETY -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Fire-Safety Context</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Why a damaged or restricted vent is worth fixing promptly</h2>

    <div class="fire-block">
      <div class="fire-label">🔥 Dryer Fire Data</div>
      <h3>FEMA and NFPA report ~15,000–16,000 annual US dryer fires</h3>
      <p>Dryer fires are a recognized residential fire-safety category. FEMA and NFPA data show approximately 15,000–16,000 dryer fires annually in US homes, with lint buildup identified as a leading ignition factor and restricted airflow a contributing accelerant. The NFPA addresses dryer and exhaust-system fire hazards in its standards for clothes dryer installation and use (NFPA Section 28 on clothes dryer fire hazards). Local fire-department advisory language across SoCal counties (LAFD, OCFA, Ventura County Fire, San Bernardino County Fire, Riverside County Fire) echoes the general NFPA guidance on vent-system maintenance frequency.</p>
      <p>The appliance-side portion of the vent system, the piece between the dryer and the wall connection, is a concentrated location for lint to accumulate because it's the first restriction point in the airflow path. A crushed transition duct, a torn lint-trap housing, or a damaged vent collar concentrates lint exactly where heat accumulates. Keeping this portion of the system mechanically intact is one of the more meaningful fire-risk reductions available at appliance-repair scope.</p>
      <p>For the full home-vent-system side of fire-risk management, the long run through walls and to exterior termination, dedicated dryer-vent-cleaning companies maintain the specialized equipment and the ongoing maintenance-cadence expertise. Apartment-building and multi-unit fire-code compliance typically requires specialist inspection and documented certification, which is outside residential appliance-repair scope.</p>
      <div class="fire-grid">
        <div class="fire-item"><strong>~15,000–16,000</strong><span>FEMA/NFPA estimate · annual US dryer fires</span></div>
        <div class="fire-item"><strong>Leading ignition factor</strong><span>Lint buildup + restricted airflow</span></div>
        <div class="fire-item"><strong>Appliance-side</strong><span>Transition duct + lint trap + vent collar · our scope</span></div>
        <div class="fire-item"><strong>Home-system side</strong><span>Walls + ceilings + roof cap · cleaning-specialist scope</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

